<chapter xml:id="chapter-counting" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
<title>Counting</title>

<section xml:id="section-counting-motivation">
<title>Motivation</title>

<p>
You probably learned to count before you even started kindergarten.
But efficiently counting large collections can be difficult!
</p>

<example>
	<title>Examples of counting large collections</title>
	<p><ul>
		<li> How many different ways can you choose your winning numbers for the lottery? </li>
		<li> How many different possible seating charts could be made for the students in this course in the assigned classroom? </li>
		<li> How many different ways are there for you to choose courses to satisfy your degree requirements? </li>
		<li> How many bijections between the sets <m> \{0,1,2,3,4,5\} </m> and <m> \{a,b,c,d,e,f\} </m> exist? </li>
		<li> How many total orders on the set <m> \{0,1,2,3,4,5\} </m> exist? </li>
		<li> How many partial orders on the set <m> \{0,1,2,3,4,5\} </m> exist? </li>
	</ul></p>
</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-counting-add-subtr-rules">
<title>Addition and subtraction rules</title>

<p> As usual in mathematics, breaking a big problem into smaller parts is a useful strategy. </p>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-counting-add-rule">
	<title>Addition Rule</title>
	<idx><h>Rule(s)</h><h>Addition</h></idx>
	<idx>Addition Rule</idx>
	<statement><p>
		Assume <m> U </m> is a finite set.
		<ol>
			<li xml:id="theorem-counting-add-rule-disj">
				If <m> U = A_1 \disjunion A_2 </m>, then <m> \card{U} = \card{A_1} + \card{A_2} </m>.
			</li>
			<li xml:id="theorem-counting-add-rule-general">
				If <m> U = A_1 \union A_2 </m>, then <m> \card{U} = \card{A_1} + \card{A_2} - \card{A_1 \intersection A_2} </m>.
			</li>
		</ol>
	</p></statement>
	<proof><title>Proof idea</title><p>
		After recalling the definition of
		<term><xref ref="definition-sets-disjoint-sets" text="custom">disjoint</xref> <xref ref="definition-sets-disjoint-union" text="custom">union</xref></term>,
		<xref ref="theorem-counting-add-rule-disj" text="local">Statement</xref> should be obvious.
		To prove <xref ref="theorem-counting-add-rule-general" text="local">Statement</xref>,
		apply <xref ref="theorem-counting-add-rule-disj" text="local">Statement</xref> to the following disjoint unions:
		<md><mrow>
			U \amp = A_1 \disjunion {(A_2 \relcmplmnt A_1)}, \amp
			A_2 \amp = {(A_2 \relcmplmnt A_1)} \disjunion {(A_1 \intersection A_2)}.
		</mrow></md>
		Then combine the resulting equalities of cardinalities.
	</p></proof>
</theorem>

<remark><p>
	<xref ref="theorem-counting-add-rule-disj" text="local">Statement</xref>
	of <xref ref="theorem-counting-add-rule" />
	can be extended to a disjoint union of any number of subsets.
</p></remark>

<problem>  <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Counting by breaking into cases</title>
	<statement><p> How many words of length <m> 3 </m> or less are there using alphabet <m> \Sigma = \{ \alpha, \omega \} </m>? </p></statement>
	<solution>
		<p>
		Write <m> \leset{\words{\Sigma}}{3} </m> to mean the set of words in alphabet <m> \Sigma </m> of length <m> 3 </m> or less.
		Then <md> \leset{\words{\Sigma}}{3} = \words{\Sigma}_0 \disjunion \words{\Sigma}_1 \disjunion \words{\Sigma}_2 \disjunion \words{\Sigma}_3 </md>,
		so we can break into cases based on length and then apply the <xref ref="theorem-counting-add-rule" text="title" />.
		</p>
		<case><title>Count <m> \words{\Sigma}_0 </m></title><p>
			There is only one word of length <m> 0 </m>: the empty word.
			So <m> \card{\words{\Sigma}_0} = 1 </m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Count <m> \words{\Sigma}_1 </m></title><p>
			There are only two words of length <m> 1 </m>: the single-letter words <m> w_\alpha = \alpha </m> and <m> w_\omega = \omega </m>.
			So <m> \card{\words{\Sigma}_1} = 2 </m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Count <m> \words{\Sigma}_2 </m></title><p>
			We can count be simply listing the elements:
			<md> \words{\Sigma}_2 = \{ \alpha \alpha, \alpha \omega, \omega \alpha, \omega \omega \} </md>.
			So <m> \card{\words{\Sigma}_2} = 4 </m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Count <m> \words{\Sigma}_3 </m></title><p>
			This time we will just use inductive reasoning.
			Each word in <m> \words{\Sigma}_2 </m> may be extended to a word in <m> \words{\Sigma}_3 </m> by appending either an <m> \alpha </m> or an <m> \omega </m> onto the end.
			So there must be twice as many words in <m> \words{\Sigma}_3 </m> as in <m> \words{\Sigma}_2 </m>,
			<ie /> <m> \card{\words{\Sigma}_3} = 8 </m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Total count</title><p>
			Using the <xref ref="theorem-counting-add-rule" text="title" />,
			we obtain the total by adding up our preliminary results:
			<md> \card{\leset{\words{\Sigma}}{3}} = 1 + 2 + 4 + 8 = 15 </md>.
		</p></case>
	</solution>
</problem>

<p> Another common strategy in mathematics is to consider the opposite. </p>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-counting-subtr-rule">
	<title>Subtraction Rule</title>
	<idx><h>Rule(s)</h><h>Subtraction</h></idx>
	<idx>Subtraction Rule</idx>
	<statement><p>
		Assume <m> U </m> is a finite set.
		For every subset <m> A \subseteq U </m>,
		we have <m> \card{A} = \card{U} - \card{\cmplmnt{A}} </m>.
	</p></statement>
	<proof><title>Proof idea</title><p>
		Since <m> U = A \disjunion \cmplmnt{A} </m> is always true,
		simply apply
		<xref ref="theorem-counting-add-rule-disj" text="local">Statement</xref>
		of <xref ref="theorem-counting-add-rule" />
		to this disjoint union and rearrange to isolate <m> \card{A} </m>.
	</p></proof>
</theorem>

<example>
	<title>Counting by counting the complement</title>
	<p>
	For alphabet <m> \Sigma = \EngAlphabet </m>,
	how many words in <m> \words{\Sigma}_2 </m> do <em>not</em> begin with the letter <m> \mathrm{a} </m>?
	It's much easier to count the number of words in <m> \words{\Sigma}_2 </m> that <em>do</em> begin with <m> \mathrm{a} </m>,
	as there are only <m> 26 </m> possibilities for the second letter.
	</p><p>
	Later in this chapter we will learn a rule that will allow us to easily calculate the total number of words in <m> \words{\Sigma}_2 </m> to be <m> 26^2 </m>
	(see <xref ref="wexample-counting-words-fixed-length" />).
	Accepting this fact for the moment,
	we can then use the <xref ref="theorem-counting-subtr-rule" text="title" /> to compute
	<md>
		<mrow>
			\ncardop \{ 2\text{-letter words not beginning with } \mathrm{a} \}
			\amp = \card{\words{\Sigma}_2} - \ncardop \{ 2\text{-letter words beginning with } \mathrm{a} \}
		</mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 26^2 - 26 </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 26 (26 - 1) </mrow>
		<mrow> \amp = 26 \cdot 25 </mrow>
	</md>.
	</p>
</example>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-counting-multiplication-rule">
<title>Multiplication rule</title>

<!-- next two had overall \label{EXAMPLE::counting.cartesian} ? -->

<problem xml:id="wexample-counting-small-cartesian"> <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Counting a small Cartesian product</title>
	<statement><p> What is <m> \card{A \cartprod B} </m> for <m> A = \{ 0, 1, 2, 3 \} </m> and <m> B = \{ -1, 0, 1 \} </m>? </p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		We can solve this by just writing out the elements of <m> A \cartprod B </m> and counting them.
		<md>
			<mrow>
				A \cartprod B \amp = \{
					(0,-1), (0,0), (0,1), (1,-1), (1,0), (1,1),
			</mrow><mrow>
				\amp \phantom{ = \{ }
					\quad (2,-1), (2,0), (2,1), (3,-1), (3,0), (3,1)
				\}
			</mrow>
		</md>
		So <m> \card{A \cartprod B} = 12 </m>.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

<problem xml:id="wexample-counting-large-cartesian"> <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Counting a large Cartesian product</title>
	<statement><p> What is <m> \card{C \cartprod D} </m> for <m> C = \{ a,b,c,\dotsc,z \} </m> and <m> D = \{0,1,2,\cdots,99 \} </m>? </p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		Writing out all the elements of <m> C \cartprod D </m> and then counting them all seems like a lot of work.
		Instead, using our experience from <xref ref="wexample-counting-small-cartesian" />,
		notice that we usually perform the task of writing the elements of a Cartesian product in a pattern to make sure we get them all.
		One-by-one we pick a single element of the first set <m> C </m>, and pair it up with <em>every</em> element of the second set <m> D </m>.
		From this pattern we see that for each <m> c \in C </m>, there are <m> \card{D} </m> elements of <m> C \cartprod D </m> with <m> c </m> as the first coordinate,
		and there are <m> \card{C} </m> such groupings of elements from <m> C \cartprod D </m>.
		So we arrive at <md>\card{C \cartprod D} = \card{C} \cdot \card{D} = 26 \cdot 100 = 2600 </md>.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

<exercise><p>
	For sets <m> X </m> and <m> Y </m>, define an equivalence relation on <m> X \cartprod Y </m> whose equivalence classes partition <m> X \cartprod Y </m> in the manner described in the provided solution to <xref ref="wexample-counting-large-cartesian" />.
	Then describe how the number of classes and the number of objects in each class correspond to <m> \card{X} </m> and <m> \card{Y} </m>.
</p></exercise>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-counting-mult-rule">
	<title>Multiplication Rule</title>
	<idx><h>Rule(s)</h><h>Multiplication</h></idx>
	<idx>Multiplication Rule</idx>
	<p>
	If there are <m> m </m> ways to perform task <m> S </m> and <m> n </m> ways to perform task <m> T </m>,
	then there are <m> m n </m> ways to perform task <m> S </m> followed by task <m> T </m>.
	</p>
</theorem>

<warning><p>
	The <xref ref="theorem-counting-mult-rule" text="title" />
	only applies to consecutive tasks <m> S,T </m> such that the number of ways of performing task <m> T </m> is <em>independent</em> of the choice made in performing task <m> S </m>.
</p></warning>

<example>
	<title>Counting Cartesian product elements by constructing an arbitrary element</title>
	<p>
	To create a specific example of an element from <m> A \cartprod B </m>,
	we must first choose an element of <m> A </m> to be the first coordinate (task <m> S </m>),
	then choose an element of <m> B </m> to be the second coordinate (task <m> T </m>).
	There are <m> m = \card{A} </m> ways to perform task <m> S </m> and <m> n = \card{B} </m> ways to perform task <m> T </m>.
	Therefore, the <xref ref="theorem-counting-mult-rule" text="title" /> says
	there are <m> m n </m> ways to construct an element of <m> A \cartprod B </m>, which means <m> \card{A\cartprod B} = m n </m>.
	</p>
</example>

<example xml:id="example-counting-candidates">
	<title>Choosing candidates</title>
	<p>
	Suppose you are a casting director and need to select both a primary actor and an understudy for the lead role in a play.
	If <m> n </m> actors audition for the role,
	then there are <m> n </m> different ways to select the primary actor.
	Once this choice is made, there remain <m> n-1 </m> different ways to the select the understudy.
	Hence there are <m> n (n - 1) </m> ways to cast the role.
	</p><p>
	Now, the actual pool of candidates for understudy will differ based on which actor is offered the lead role.
	However, no matter who is chosen for the lead, the <em>number</em> of remaining candidates for understudy is the same.
	</p>
</example>

<note><p> We may extend the <xref ref="theorem-counting-mult-rule" text="title" /> to any (finite) number of consecutive tasks. </p></note>

<example><title>Cardinality of Cartesian product of many sets</title><p>
	If <m> A_1,A_2,\dotsc,A_m </m> are finite sets with <m> \card{A_j} = m_j </m>,
	then <md> \card{A_1 \cartprod A_2 \cartprod \dotsb \cartprod A_\ell} = m_1 m_2 \dotsm m_\ell </md>.
</p></example>

<problem xml:id="wexample-counting-words-fixed-length"> <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Words of a given length</title>
	<statement><p>
		Recall that, given alphabet <m> \Sigma </m> and number <m> n \in \N </m>,
		<m> \words{\Sigma}_n </m> is the set of words of length <m> n </m>.
		If <m> \card{\Sigma} = m </m>, what is <m> \card{\words{\Sigma}_n} </m>?
	</p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		To construct a specific example word <m> w \in \words{\Sigma}_n </m>, there are:
		<ul>
			<li> <m> m </m> ways to choose the first letter, </li>
			<li> <m> m </m> ways to choose the second letter, </li>
			<li> <ellipsis />, </li>
			<li> <m> m </m> ways to choose the <m> \nth </m> letter. </li>
		</ul>
		So there are
		<md> \underbrace{m \cdot m \cdot m \cdot \dotsb \cdot m}_{n \text{ factors}} = m^n </md>
		ways to construct <m> w </m>.
		We conclude <m> \card{\words{\Sigma}_n} = m^n </m>.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

<problem xml:id="wexample-counting-words-no-repeats"> <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Words with no repeated letters</title>
	<statement><p>
		Suppose <m> \card{\Sigma} = 5 </m>.
		How many words in <m> \card{\words{\Sigma}_5} </m> have no repeated letters?
		(That is, in which no two letters are the same?)
	</p></statement>
	<solution>
		<p>
		To construct a specific example word <m> w \in \words{\Sigma}_5 </m>
		in which no two letters are the same,
		there are
		<ul>
			<li> <m> 5 </m> ways to choose the first letter, </li>
			<li> <m> 4 </m> remaining ways to choose the second letter, </li>
			<li> <m> 3 </m> remaining ways to choose the third letter, </li>
			<li> <m> 2 </m> remaining ways to choose the fourth letter, and </li>
			<li> only <m> 1 </m> remaining way to choose the last letter. </li>
		</ul>
		So there are
		<md> 5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1 = 120 </md>
		ways to construct <m> w </m>.
		</p><p>
		Similar to <xref ref="example-counting-candidates" />,
		while the actual pool of candidates for the next letter at each step will differ based on which letters have been chosen already,
		the <em>number</em> of remaining letters is always independent of which letters have actually been chosen so far.
		So the <xref ref="theorem-counting-mult-rule" text="title" /> can be applied to this problem exactly as we have applied it.
		</p>
	</solution>
</problem>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Palindromes</title>
	<statement><p>
		Let <m> \Sigma = \EngAlphabet </m>.
		How many palindromes <m> w </m> with <m> 3 \le \length{w} \le 6 </m> are there in <m> \words{\Sigma} </m>?
	</p></statement>
	<solution>
		<p> Break into cases based on the length of <m> w </m>. </p>
		<case><title>Case <m> \length{w} = 3 </m></title><p>
			Once we choose the first letter, the last is chosen for us, but we are still free to choose the middle letter.
			So there are <m> 26^2 </m> palindromes of length <m> 3 </m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Case <m> \length{w} = 4 </m></title><p>
			Once we choose the first two letters, the last two are chosen for us.
			So there are also <m> 26^2 </m> palindromes of length <m> 4 </m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Case <m> \length{w} = 5 </m></title><p>
			Once we choose the first two letters, the last two are chosen for us, but we are still free to choose the middle letter.
			So there are <m> 26^3 </m> palindromes of length <m> 5 </m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Case <m> \length{w} = 6 </m></title><p>
			Once we choose the first three letters, the last three are chosen for us.
			So there are also <m> 26^3 </m> palindromes of length <m> 6 </m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Total</title><p>
			Applying the <xref ref="theorem-counting-add-rule" text="title" /> to these non-overlapping cases, we obtain
			<md>
			 	<mrow> 26^2 + 26^2 + 26^3 + 26^3 \amp = 26^2(1+1+26+26) </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 54 \cdot 26^2 </mrow>
				<mrow> \amp = 36,504 </mrow>
			</md>
			as the number of palindromes length <m> 3 </m> to <m> 6 </m>.
		</p></case>
	</solution>
</problem>

<problem xml:id="wexample-counting-functions"> <!-- worked example -->
<!-- \label{WEXAMPLE::counting.functions} -->
	<statement><p>
		Set <m> A = \{a,b,c\} </m> and <m> B = \{0,1,2,3,4\} </m>.
		How many functions <m> A \to B </m> exist?
		How many of these are injections?
		How many are surjections?
	</p></statement>
	<solution>
		<case><title>Number of functions</title><p>
			A function <m> \funcdef{f}{A}{B} </m> can be constructed in three steps:
			choose <m> f(a) </m>, then choose <m> f(b) </m>, then choose <m> f(c) </m>.
			Each of the steps can be carried out in <m> \card{B} = 5 </m> ways.
			So the number of functions is <m> 5^3 = 125 </m>.
		</p></case>
		<case><title>Number of injections</title>
			<p>
			An injection <m> \ifuncdef{f}{A}{B} </m> can be constructed in three steps:
			choose <m> f(a) </m>,
			then choose <m> f(b) </m> to be <em>different from</em> <m> f(a) </m>,
			then choose <m> f(c) </m> to be <em>different from both</em> <m> f(a) </m> and <m> f(b) </m>.
			First step has <m> \card{B} = 5 </m> choices.
			Second step has <m> \card{ B \relcmplmnt \{f(a)\} } = 4 </m> choices.
			Third step has <m> \card{ B \relcmplmnt \{f(a),f(b)\} } = 3 </m> choices.
			So the number of injections is <m> 5 \cdot 4 \cdot 3 = 60 </m>.
			</p>
			<aside><title>A look ahead</title><p>
				Notice that the number of injections has turned out to be
				<md> \frac{\card{B}!}{(\card{B} - \card{A})!} </md>.
				We will understand better how this formula arises in <xref ref="section-permutations-subsets" />.
			</p></aside>
		</case>
		<case><title>Number of surjections</title><p>
			Suppose <m> \funcdef{f}{A}{B} </m>.
			Since <m> \card{A} = 3 </m>, the <em>largest</em> that <m> \card{f(A)} </m> can be is <m> 3 </m>, which occurs when <m> f </m> is injective.
			However, even in such a largest case it is still smaller then <m> \card{B} </m>, so no surjections exist.
			That is, the number of surjections is <m> 0 </m>.
		</p></case>
	</solution>
</problem>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-counting-division-rule">
<title>Division rule</title>

<p>
Sometimes it is easier to count a related but more structured collection,
where the collection we actually want to count corresponds to equivalence classes of the more structured collection.
</p>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-counting-div-rule">
	<title>Division Rule</title>
	<idx><h>Rule(s)</h><h>Division</h></idx>
	<idx>Division Rule</idx>
	<statement><p>
		Suppose <m> \mathord{\equiv} </m> is an equivalence relation on a finite set <m> A </m> so that the equivalence classes
		<alert>all have the same number of elements</alert>.
		Then
		<md> \ncardop \{ \text{equivalence classes} \} = \frac{\card{A}}{\text{common size of classes}} </md>.
		That is,
		<md> \card{A / \mathord{\equiv}} = \frac{\card{A}}{\card{\eqclass{a}}} </md>,
		where <m> a </m> is an arbitrary element of <m> A </m>.
	</p></statement>
	<proof><p>
		Write <m> N </m> for the number of equivalence classes,
		and write <m> C </m> for the common cardinality of the classes.
		We know that the equivalence classes partition the set <m> A </m>,
		so using the <xref ref="theorem-counting-add-rule" text="title" /> we have
		<md> \card{A} = \card{\eqclass{a_1}} + \card{\eqclass{a_2}} + \dotsb + \card{\eqclass{a_N}} </md>,
		where <m> a_1, a_2, \dotsc, a_N </m> are a <xref ref="definition-equiv-rel-complete-rep-set" text="title" />.
		But we have assumed that these class cardinalities are all equal to each other,
		with each class satisfying <m> \card{\eqclass{a_j}} = C </m>.
		So <md> \card{A} = \underbrace{C + C + \dotsb + C}_{N \text{ terms}} = N C </md>,
		which leads to <md> N = \frac{\card{A}}{C} </md>,
		as desired.
	</p></proof>
</theorem>

<problem>  <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Equivalent words</title>
	<statement><p>
		Let <m> \Sigma = \{ \alpha, \beta, \gamma \} </m>.
		How many words in <m> \words{\Sigma}_4 </m> contain exactly two <m> \alpha </m>s, one <m> \beta </m> and one <m> \gamma </m>?
	</p></statement>
	<solution>
		<p>
		Write <m> \Lambda </m> for the collection of words in <m> \words{\Sigma}_4 </m> of the type described.
		Instead of trying to count <m> \Lambda </m> directly, consider the following more structured collection.
		</p><p>
		Write <m> \Sigma' = \{\alpha_1, \alpha_2, \beta, \gamma\} </m>,
		and let <m> \Lambda' </m> be the set of words in <m> \words{(\Sigma')}_4 </m> that have no repeated letters.
		Similar to <xref ref="wexample-counting-words-no-repeats" />,
		we have
		<md> \card{\Lambda'} = 4 \cdot 3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1 = 24 </md>.
		For each pair of these words, write <m> w_1 \equiv w_2 </m> if the following two conditions hold.
		<ol marker="(i)">
			<li>
				At whatever position <m> w_1 </m> contains <m> \alpha_1 </m>,
				<m> w_2 </m> contains either <m> \alpha_1 </m> or <m> \alpha_2 </m> at that same position.
			</li>
			<li>
				At whatever position <m> w_1 </m> contains <m> \alpha_2 </m>,
				<m> w_2 </m> contains either <m> \alpha_1 </m> or <m> \alpha_2 </m> at that same position.
			</li>
		</ol>
		You may check that <m> \mathord{\equiv} </m> defines an equivalence relation on <m> \Lambda' </m>.
		Each class consists of exactly two words <m> \{w_1,w_2\} </m>,
		where <m> w_2 </m> has an <m> \alpha_2 </m> where <m> w_1 </m> has an <m> \alpha_1 </m> and an <m> \alpha_1 </m> where <m> w_1 </m> has an <m> \alpha_2 </m>.
		For example, one class of <m> \Lambda' / \mathord{\equiv} </m> is
		<md> \eqclass{\alpha_1 \beta \alpha_2 \gamma} = \{ \alpha_1 \beta \alpha_2 \gamma, \alpha_2 \beta \alpha_1 \gamma \} </md>.
		Effectively, the classes remove the distinction between <m> \alpha_1 </m> and <m> \alpha_2 </m>,
		so that they might as well be the same letter, say, <m> \alpha </m>.
		In other words, there is a bijective correspondence between the classes in <m> \Lambda' / \mathord{\equiv} </m> and the words in <m> \Lambda </m>.
		Using the <xref ref="theorem-counting-div-rule" text="title" />, we have
		<md> \card{\Lambda} = \card{\Lambda' / \mathord{\equiv}} = \frac{\card{\Lambda'}}{2} = \frac{24}{2} = 12 </md>.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

</section>

<section xml:id="section-counting-pigeon">
<title>Pigeonhole principle</title>

<subsection>
<title>Regular strength version</title>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-counting-pigeon">
	<title>Pigeonhole Principle (formal version)</title>
	<idx><h>Principle</h><h>Pigeonhole</h><h>formal version</h></idx>
	<idx><h>Pigeonhole Principle</h><h>formal version</h></idx>
	<statement><p> If <m> A,B </m> are finite sets with <m> \card{B} \lt \card{A} </m>, then no function <m> A \to B </m> can be an injection. </p></statement>
	<proof><p>
		This principle is just the contrapositive of
		<xref ref="fact-cardinality-subset-of-finite-inj-image" text="local">Statement</xref>
		of <xref ref="fact-cardinality-subset-of-finite" />.
	</p></proof>
</theorem>

<corollary xml:id="corollary-counting-pigeon">
	<title>Pigeonhole Principle</title>
	<idx><h>Principle</h><h>Pigeonhole</h></idx>
	<idx>Pigeonhole Principle</idx>
	<statement><p>
		If <m> m </m> objects are placed in <m> n </m> containers, where <m> m \gt n </m>,
		then at least one container must contain more than one object.
	</p></statement>
	<proof><p>
		Let <m> A </m> be the set of objects and <m> B </m> the set of containers,
		so that <md> \card{B} = n \lt m = \card{A} </md>.
		Also let <m> \funcdef{f}{A}{B} </m> represent the function where <m> f(a) = b </m> means that object <m> a </m> has been placed in container <m> b </m>.
		Then the <xref ref="theorem-counting-pigeon" /> tells us that <m> f </m> cannot be an injection,
		which means that there is at least one pair of distinct objects <m> a_1,a_2 </m> with <m> f(a_1) = f(a_2) </m>.
	</p></proof>
</corollary>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Too few seats</title>
	<statement><p>
		Your car has five seats, but you also have five friends who need a ride home.
		How will everyone fit?
	</p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		Using the people who need to get home (<ie /> your friends <em>and</em> you) as objects and car seats as containers,
		<xref ref="corollary-counting-pigeon" text="title" /> says that someone will have to sit on someone else's lap.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Dessert logistics</title>
	<statement><p>
		The cafeteria puts out <m> 200 </m> chocolate puddings and <m> 200 </m> tapioca puddings.
		If <m> 201 </m> students each grab a bowl of pudding,
		what is the <em>minimum</em> number of tapioca puddings that have been taken?
	</p></statement>
	<solution>
		<p>
		Since <m> 201 \gt 200 </m>, there is no injection
		<md> \{\text{students who took a pudding}\} \ifuncto \{\text{bowls of chocolate pudding}\} </md>.
		(<em>Or:</em> use students as objects, bowls of chocolate pudding as containers.)
		</p><p>
		But we can't actually have two students take the same bowl of pudding,
		so at least one student must eat tapioca.
		</p>
	</solution>
</problem>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Matching pairs</title>
	<statement><p>
		Suppose <m> A \subseteq \{1,2,\dotsc, 20\} </m>.
		How big must <m> \card{A} </m> be to ensure that there exist two elements of <m> A </m> whose sum is <m> 21 </m>?
	</p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		Collect together the (unordered) pairs of numbers that add to <m> 21 </m>:
		<md> B = \bigl\{ \{1,20\}, \{2,19\}, \dotsc, \{10,11\} \bigr\} \subseteq \powset{\{1,2,\dotsc, 20\}} </md>.
		Notice that <m> \card{B} = 10 </m>.
		Thinking of the elements of <m> B </m> as containers and elements of <m> A </m> as objects,
		place object <m> a </m> into container <m> b </m> if <m> a \in b </m>.
		We need one more object than container to ensure some container receives two objects, so the answer is <m> \card{A} \ge 11 </m>.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

<problem>
	<title>Matching modulo <m> m </m></title>
	<statement><p>
		Suppose <m> m \in \N </m> and <m> A \subseteq \N </m> such that <m> 0 \lt m \lt \card{A} \lt \infty </m>.
		Show that there exist distinct <m> a_1,a_2 \in A </m> that have the same remainder when divided by <m> m </m>.
	</p></statement>
	<solution>
		<p>
		The set of possible remainders is <m> \natnumlt{m} = \{0,1,2,\cdots,m-1\} </m>.
		Computing remainder after division by <m> m </m> defines a function <m> A \to \natnumlt{m} </m>.
		Since <m> \card{\natnumlt{m}} = m \lt \card{A} </m>, this function cannot be an injection.
		</p><p>
		(<em>Or:</em> use elements of <m> A </m> as objects, possible remainders when dividing a number by <m> m </m> as containers.)
		</p>
	</solution>
</problem>

</subsection>

<subsection>
<title>Strong version</title>

<p>
Recall that given a function <m> \funcdef{f}{A}{B} </m>, we can define an equivalence relation <m> \mathord{\equiv} </m> on <m> A </m> by taking <m> a_1 \equiv a_2 </m> to mean <m> f(a_1) = f(a_2) </m>
(see <xref ref="example-equiv-rel-eq-func-image" />).
In this way, we can regard <m> f </m> as placing objects (elements of <m> A </m>) into containers (elements of <m> B </m>),
so that object <m> a \in A </m> is <q>placed</q> in container <m> b \in B </m> when <m> f(a) = b </m>.
</p>

<theorem xml:id="theorem-counting-strong-pigeon">
	<title>Pigeonhole Principle (strong form, formal version)</title>
	<idx><h>Principle</h><h>Pigeonhole</h><h>strong form (formal version)</h></idx>
	<idx><h>Pigeonhole Principle</h><h>strong form (formal version)</h></idx>
	<statement>
		<p>
		Suppose <m> \funcdef{f}{A}{B} </m>, with <m> A,B </m> finite,
		and let <m> \mathord{\equiv} </m> be the equivalence relation on <m> A </m> where <m> a_1 \equiv a_2 </m> means <m> f(a_1) = f(a_2) </m>.
		</p><p>
		If <m> \card{A} \gt \ell \cdot \card{B} </m> for some <m> \ell \in \N </m>,
		then at least one of the equivalence classes of <m> A </m> with respect to <m> \mathord{\equiv} </m> has more than <m> \ell </m> elements.
		</p>
	</statement>
	<proof>
		<p> Consider the contrapositive: </p>
		<blockquote><p>
			if <em>every</em> equivalence class of <m> A </m> has <em>no more</em> than <m> \ell </m> elements, then <m> \card{A} \le \ell \cdot \card{B} </m>.
		</p></blockquote>
		<p>
		Since <m> B </m> is finite and <m> f(A) \subseteq B </m>, then also <m> f(A) </m> is finite and we can enumerate its elements.
		Write <m> f(A) = \{ b_1, b_2, \dotsc, b_n \} </m>. Each element of <m> f(A) </m> corresponds to an equivalence class of <m> A </m>.
		</p>
		<figure xml:id="figure-counting-strong-pigeon">
			<caption>Diagram of equivalence classes under the <q>have same image</q> equivalence.</caption>
			<image xml:id="image-counting-strong-pigeon" width="67.9%">
				<description>Diagram of equivalence classes under the <q>have same image</q> equivalence.</description>
				<latex-image><xi:include href="counting.d/strong-pigeon.tex" parse="text" /></latex-image>
			</image>
		</figure>
		<p>
		In this diagram, the <m> a_i </m> are representative elements of the class of elements of <m> A </m> that are mapped to <m> b_i </m> by <m> f </m>.
		In particular, we must have <m> f(a_i) = b_i </m> for each index <m> i </m>.
		</p><p>
		We are assuming that each class <m> [a_i] </m> contains no more than <m> \ell </m> elements;
		<ie /> <m> \card{[a_i]} \le \ell </m>.
		Since an equivalence relation always partitions a set <m> A </m> into the disjoint union of its equivalence classes, we have
		<md>
			<mrow> \card{A} \amp = \card{[a_1]} + \card{[a_2]} + \dotsb + \card{[a_n]} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp \le \underbrace{\ell + \ell + \dotsb + \ell}_{r \text{ terms}} </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \ell n </mrow>
			<mrow> \amp = \ell \cdot \card{f(A)}. </mrow>
		</md>
		But <m> f(A) </m> is a subset of the finite set <m> B </m>, and so <m> \card{f(A)} \le \card{B} </m>.
		Combining this with the calculation above gives <md> \card{A} \le \ell \cdot \card{f(A)} \le \ell \cdot \card{B} </md>.
		</p>
	</proof>
</theorem>

<corollary xml:id="corollary-counting-strong-pigeon">
	<title>Pigeonhole Principle (strong form, informal version)</title>
	<idx><h>Principle</h><h>Pigeonhole</h><h>strong form (informal version)</h></idx>
	<idx><h>Pigeonhole Principle</h><h>strong form (informal version)</h></idx>
	<statement><p>
		If <m> m </m> objects are placed in <m> n </m> containers, with <m> m \gt \ell n </m> for some <m> \ell \in \N </m>,
		then at least one container contains more than <m> \ell </m> objects.
	</p></statement>
	<proof><title>Proof idea</title><p>
		Again, let <m> A </m> be the set of objects and <m> B </m> the set of containers,
		so that <md> \card{A} = m \gt \ell n = \ell \cdot \card{B} </md>.
		Then apply the <xref ref="theorem-counting-strong-pigeon" text="title" />.
	</p></proof>
</corollary>

<note><p>
	The <xref ref="theorem-counting-strong-pigeon" text="title"/>
	is a <em>generalization</em> of
	the <xref ref="theorem-counting-pigeon" text="title" />.
	A function is an injection precisely when no two distinct elements of the domain produce the same output image,
	so using <m> \ell = 1 </m> in the strong form gives back the original form.
</p></note>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Handing out coins</title>
	<statement><p>
		Show that if thirteen coins are distributed to six children,
		then at least one child will receive at least three coins.
	</p></statement>
	<solution><p>
		Using coins as objects and children as containers, the given statement is just the <xref ref="theorem-counting-strong-pigeon" text="title" />
		with <m> \ell = 2 </m>:
		we have <m> 13 </m> objects and <m> 6 </m> containers, and <m> 13 \gt 2 \cdot 6 </m>.
		(<em>Note:</em> Since coins are discrete objects, <q>more than two</q> and <q>at least three</q> are the same thing.)
	</p></solution>
</problem>

<remark><p>
	It is worthwhile to think about how the strong form of the Pigeonhole Principle could be proved directly.
	Consider the diagram in <xref ref="figure-counting-strong-pigeon" />:
	the <q>tipping point</q> between <m> \card{A} \le \ell \cdot \card{B} </m> and <m> \card{A} \gt \ell \cdot \card{B} </m> is when <m> f </m> is surjective and each of the equivalence classes has exactly <m> \ell </m> elements.
	When <m> f </m> is surjective, there are <m> \card{B} </m> equivalence classes in <m> A </m>.
	Since <m> A </m> is the disjoint union of its equivalence classes under <m> \equiv </m>, we have <m> \card{A} = \ell \cdot \card{B} </m>.
	If we add <em>one more</em> element to <m> A </m>, it will have to be included in one of the equivalence classes,
	and that class will now have size greater than <m> \ell </m>.
</p></remark>

<problem> <!-- worked example -->
	<title>Handing out pudding</title>
	<statement><p>
		The cafeteria puts out <m> 100 </m> chocolate, <m> 100 </m> tapioca, and <m> 100 </m> butterscotch puddings.
		How many students must grab a pudding before we can be certain that at least one of the flavours has at least half of the bowls taken?
	</p></statement>
	<solution><title>Using <q>tipping point</q> thinking</title><p>
		The <q>tipping point</q> is exactly <m> 49 </m> bowls of <em>each</em> flavour taken,
		which requires <m> 3\cdot 49 = 147 </m> students.
		After the <m> \nth[148] </m> student, we will definitely have <m> 50 </m> bowls of one of the flavours taken.
	</p></solution>
	<solution><title>Direct use of the Pigeonhole Principle</title><p>
		Consider students as objects (<m> m </m> of them <mdash /> this is the unknown to be determined) and flavours as containers (<m> 3 </m> of them).
		To determine the appropriate value of <m> \ell </m> to use, consider that <q>at least half</q> in this problem means <q>at least <m> 50 </m></q>,
		which is the same as <q>more than <m> 49 </m></q>.
		So choose <m> \ell = 49 </m>.
		In that case, we need <m> m \gt 49 \cdot 3 = 147 </m>, bringing us to the answer of <m> m = 147 + 1 = 148 </m> students.
	</p></solution>
</problem>

</subsection>

</section>

<xi:include href="./counting.d/activities.ptx" />
